The following passage describes a runtime weight precision swap mechanism for on-device large language model inference. Read it carefully and continue the explanation. The key insight is that during a precision swap, weights of individual layers are replaced atomically while decoding continues, and the choice of how many layers to swap per decode step controls the latency profile observed by the user. Specifically, models with larger weight sizes may exhibit longer latency if they perform more swaps at each decode step; conversely models with fewer weight sizes may have shorter latencies when switching precision less often.

